properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A disturbance over north central Montana will track northeastward into the central grainbelt tonight bringing rain, thunderstorms and strong winds to the region. Thunderstorms initially associated with this disturbance will weaken tonight but form a general area of widespread rain over the northwestern grainbelt. As this time the highest rainfall amounts of 20 to 40 mm are expected north of Kindersley to Meadow Lake and west of Saskatoon to the Alberta boundary. Some areas may see in excess of 50 mm by Wednesday evening especially under thunderstorms. The precipitation will likely linger Wednesday night but diminish in intensity Over the southwestern corner of the province, this includes Leader, Swift Current, the Cypress Hills and Shaunavon, as the disturbance tracks into the central grainbelt severe thunderstorms will exit the region this evening. However, on Wednesday, strong west to northwest winds are forecast to develop on the back side of this system with winds gusts in the 80-90 km/h range by Wednesday afternoon. The winds will gradually diminish Wednesday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Tornado Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of severe thunderstorms which may produce tornadoes. Severe thunderstorms will develop in the late afternoon and will initially be discrete before coalescing into a line in the evening and overnight period. During the initial convective period, as these storms are discrete, there will be an enhanced risk for tornadoes to form with these severe thunderstorms. There is the risk for a long track tornado with the development of these supercells. ### This is a dangerous and potentially life-threatening situation. Tornado watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce tornadoes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
